### A staff-level interview primer

Companion to the correctness/operability primer. This one is about what happens when multiple independent workloads share the same capacity.

---

## 1. What a staff engineer actually needs to know

Multi-tenancy = one system serving multiple independent clients (tenants, priority classes, request types) over shared capacity. Fairness = no tenant dominates or starves another outside designed policy.

Interviews test:
- Spotting starvation and head-of-line (HOL) blocking in proposed designs
- Picking the right tool — admission control vs scheduling vs isolation — for the scenario
- Reasoning about noisy neighbors in shared resources (cache, threads, GPU memory)
- Defending the choice of fair-queue algorithm
- Translating fairness to variable-cost workloads (LLM inference, batch queries)

Skip for most roles: formal scheduling theory, BGP/ATM queueing math, CFS internals. You need a working vocabulary, not academic depth.

**"Fair" does not mean "equal."** Fair means each tenant gets the share they paid/were configured for, and nobody can cheat. Policy (equal / weighted / priority-with-reservation) is yours to design; mechanism enforces it.

