## 2. Core mental model

Three levers control tenant behavior. Pick deliberately at each layer.

```
┌──────────────┐     ┌──────────────┐     ┌──────────────┐
│  ADMISSION   │────►│  SCHEDULING  │────►│  ISOLATION   │
│  CONTROL     │     │              │     │              │
│  "accept?"   │     │ "run next?"  │     │ "contain"    │
└──────────────┘     └──────────────┘     └──────────────┘
  at the edge         in the queue        resource boundary
  rate limits         priority / WFQ      separate pools
  quotas              preemption          bulkheads
  load shed           aging               cells
  cheap, coarse       cheap, granular     strong, expensive
```

If you only pick one: **isolation is the strongest guarantee** but expensive. **Scheduling** is granular but fair only if admission has capped inflight. **Admission** is cheap but blunt. Production systems use all three in layers.

Why this matters:
- Shared caches, thread pools, queues, GPU memory, connection pools all couple tenants
- Variable-cost workloads amplify unfairness (a 100× request can't fairly share with a 1× request under request-count fairness)
- A single misbehaving tenant can melt the whole system without isolation

