## 3. The problems

### Starvation
A workload waits forever because higher-priority work keeps arriving.

```
  Strict priority, no aging:
  High:  [R1][R2][R3][R4][R5][R6]... (new arrivals)
  Low:   [L1]   ← never runs
```

Fixes: **aging** (effective priority rises with wait time), **reserved capacity** for low-pri (guaranteed N% regardless of high-pri backlog), or **WFQ / DRR** instead of strict priority.

### Head-of-line (HOL) blocking
A slow request at the front of a single queue blocks cheap work behind it.

```
  [slow 10s] [fast 10ms] [fast 10ms] [fast 10ms]
     │
     └─► 3 cheap requests wait ~10s each
```

Fixes: **multiple queues** keyed by cost class, **work-stealing workers**, **preemption**, **request size classification at admit**, **SRPT** (shortest-remaining-first) with aging.

### Priority inversion
A low-priority task holds a resource a high-priority task needs; a medium-priority task preempts the low-pri; high-pri now effectively waits on the medium-pri.

```
  H (high)   needs lock L held by Lp (low)
  M (medium) arrives, preempts Lp on CPU
  L still locked — Lp can't progress
  H blocked on L, can't preempt M
  → H is effectively below M. This is the inversion.
```

Famous case: Mars Pathfinder (1997). In practice, it shows up wherever priority classes share:
- a database connection pool
- a rate-limiter token
- a config/lease cache
- a mutex in shared code

Fixes: **priority inheritance** (lock holder temporarily inherits max waiter's priority), **priority ceiling protocol**, or **eliminate shared mutable state** between priority classes (separate pools).

### Noisy neighbor
One tenant's traffic degrades another's SLO through any shared resource.

```
  Tenant A: 500 QPS, heavy batch workload, big requests
  Tenant B: 10 QPS, latency-critical

  Shared: thread pool, cache, GPU KV memory
  → B's p99 explodes because A saturates what B needs
```

Fixes (strong → weak): **dedicated cells** per top-tier tenant, **bulkheads** (separate pools per class), **per-tenant quotas** (cgroups, ResourceQuota, token-work budgets), **rate limits per tenant**.

### Convoy effects
Bursts of similar requests self-synchronize and amplify contention. Shows up around locks and in JVM GC-paused systems. Mitigate with admission jitter and per-request timeouts so convoys break up.

### Backpressure failures
No signal goes upstream when downstream is full → queues grow unbounded → latency explodes → timeouts → retries → death spiral.

```
  Missing backpressure:
  Client ──┐
           ▼
         Queue ──► grows unbounded ──► latency ↑ ──► timeouts ↑ ──► retries ↑ ──► collapse

  With backpressure:
  Client ◄─── 429 / flow-control ──── Server (queue > threshold)
```

Fixes: **explicit backpressure** (429, flow control, circuit break), **bounded queues with drop policy**, **deadline propagation** so old work is dropped not executed.

