## 5. Multi-tenancy in LLM inference (why this breaks naive fairness)

Classical multi-tenant scheduling assumes roughly uniform request cost. LLM inference violates this hard.

- **Variable cost.** A 100-input/50-output request costs ~1% of 32K-input/2K-output. Request-count fairness is wrong; fairness must be in **token-work units** (prefill FLOPs + decode FLOPs + KV-bytes-seconds).
- **Unknown output length.** True cost isn't known until the request finishes. Admission must use an estimator with a margin; the scheduler needs a kill path for runaways.
- **Shared KV memory.** All concurrent requests share GPU HBM for KV. One long-context request can starve many short ones of *memory*, not compute.
- **Continuous batching couples tenants.** Every active request shares every decode step's batch. Admitting, preempting, or completing any request changes batch shape.
- **Prefix cache breaks CPU-time fairness.** A request that hits a warm prefix is 10× cheaper than one that misses. Equal GPU time ≠ equal user latency. Routing policy interacts with fairness.
- **Spec decoding adds hidden cost.** Target model runs even on rejection. Per-tenant metering should account for it.

Implication: **token-work quotas + context-length tiers + prefix-aware routing with overload override** is the minimum viable fairness design.

