## 6. Interview reasoning patterns

**"How do you prevent one tenant from degrading another?"**
Layered. Per-tenant rate limit at admit → per-tenant token-work quota → DRR scheduler across tenants → bulkheaded worker pools for priority classes → dedicated cells for top tenants. Name the layer, name the guarantee it provides, name what it doesn't cover.

**"FIFO vs priority vs WFQ — how do you choose?"**
Uniform cost, no tiers → FIFO + admission rate limit. SLO tiers, uniform cost → strict priority + aging + reserved low-pri share. Variable cost, tenant fairness → DRR with cost-weighted quantum.

**"What's the blast radius of a runaway tenant?"**
Only as small as your weakest isolation layer. Without isolation: all tenants. With per-tenant RL: that tenant × the RL duration. With bulkhead: one pool. With cell: one cell. Explicit answer beats hand-waving.

**"How do you shed load?"**
Priority-aware, deadline-aware, at the admission layer. Shed lowest priority first. Shed requests that can't meet SLO anyway. LIFO when admitting under overload (newer requests more likely to be wanted). Prefer rejecting at admit over timing out mid-flight.

**"Where's HOL blocking in this design?"**
Walk every queue in the design. Any FIFO with mixed-cost traffic is a candidate. Any lock ordering between priority classes is a priority-inversion candidate.

**"How do you design rate limiting for a distributed API?"**
Key by tenant ID + operation class. Token bucket per key. Distributed state via Redis (atomic INCR + TTL) or local counters with leader-coordinated gossip. Return 429 with Retry-After. Include request cost, not just count, for variable-cost APIs.

