## 7. Common candidate mistakes

- Treating "one queue" as acceptable in any multi-tenant design
- Strict priority without aging or reserved low-pri share → starvation
- `1 request = 1 unit` fairness in variable-cost workloads
- Rate-limiting by IP instead of tenant (NATs bypass it)
- Ignoring priority inversion around shared locks / tokens / pools
- Unbounded queues (no backpressure → death spiral)
- Shedding at workers instead of at admission (wasted work)
- Shared thread pool across priority classes (no bulkhead)
- Ignoring the prefix cache when reasoning about inference fairness
- Assuming downstream rate limiters know tenant identity (they usually don't)
- No deadline propagation → systems do stale work

